Debouncing is a technique used in programming to prevent functions from being called too frequently, by delaying their execution if the function is called again within a certain time period.

```javascript
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timeout;
  return function() {
    var args = arguments;
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => {
      fn.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  }
}
```

Here's an example of how to use the debounce function with a `click` event handler:

```javascript
const button = document.getElementById('myButton');

document.addEventListener('click', debounce(() => {
  console.log('Button clicked!');
}, 1000));
```

In this example, the `console.log` function will only be executed if there are no new clicks within 1 second (1000 milliseconds) of the previous click.
